  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework named Graded Spatio-Temporal Meta-Adaptation (GST-Meta) for robust time series forecasting under evolving extreme conditions. The core innovation lies in replacing discrete regime classification with a continuous, learnable 'Extremeness Sensitivity Index' (ESI)—a dynamic latent signal that quantifies the degree and spatial footprint of potential extreme behavior at each time step. Instead of hard routing to separate normal/extreme branches, GST-Meta employs a graded attention mechanism that modulates feature extraction, memory retention, and loss weighting along a spectrum from normal to extreme. The ESI is jointly optimized through three interconnected modules: (1) A Spatio-Temporal Extreme Manifold Encoder that learns a low-dimensional representation of extremeness patterns using a graph-augmented Transformer, where nodes represent sensors, assets, or regions, and edges encode functional similarity or physical connectivity. This encoder captures how extreme behaviors co-evolve across space. (2) A Meta-Distribution Dynamics Forecaster—an enhanced version of DDG-DA’s predictor—that forecasts not only mean and variance but also tail thickness (e.g., GPD shape parameter) and spatial coherence of extremes over a short horizon. These forecasts are mapped to prior ESI values, enabling proactive adjustment. (3) A Differentiable Adaptive Computation Time (dACT) module that allocates computational depth (i.e., number of Transformer layers applied) per time step and location based on ESI, increasing processing fidelity in high-sensitivity regions. Critically, the entire system is trained end-to-end with a multi-objective meta-loss: one component optimizes prediction accuracy (via quantile regression), another enforces smoothness and interpretability of ESI trajectories, and a third maximizes early warning capability (measured by lead time between ESI rise and actual extreme). To handle imbalance, we introduce Synthetic Extreme Trajectory Augmentation (SETA), which generates plausible extreme sequences by perturbing historical paths along the learned manifold, preserving temporal and spatial consistency. This avoids overfitting to few real extremes. Applications span wildfire spread prediction, systemic financial risk monitoring, and urban infrastructure stress forecasting—domains where understanding the gradation and propagation of extremes is more valuable than binary detection. By unifying graded sensitivity, spatial propagation, and predictive adaptation, GST-Meta enables earlier, more reliable, and spatially coherent warnings under non-stationary, imbalanced conditions.",
